I like how the Orthodox Church holds the ringing of those huge church bells drives away demons, devils, etc. but apparently they weren't used until like the 7th and 8th century. Implies that in the future we can potentially discover more demon-repelling tools we don't know about.

Reading some articles on the history of church bells and apparently the peak of the science was reached in the 16th and 17th century in Russia where church bells were "accurate to under 1%". Even church bells produced today with modern methods can't reach their level of accuracy.

The foundry was next to Assumption Cathedral in Rostov Veliky so I guess if you go to Russia you can visit Rostov Veliky and hear them if they still have the old bells there. Church bells and their history seem like one of those topics you can easily dedicate your entire life to.

Final note on the wine book, but the recommended daily dosage of wine for active athletes according to a "Dr. Encausse" was "three-quarters of a liter of wine, either a Bordeaux or a light Beaujolais" and the book chapter finishes by calling wine the perfect bodybuilder food. üá´üá∑.

Les Stroud was talking about how in a survival situation not getting enough sleep is one of the biggest dangers because if you are sleep deprived you can start acting irrationally, get disoriented, miss signs/food, etc. Gamers and survivalists often face the same health problems.

It's like people sort of superstitiously believe if they keep saying "vibe shift" they are manifesting the cultural changes they hope for, like how at the horse racing bets they scream their horse's name. It feels filthy in the same way as a multilevel marketing pyramid scheme.

Statistically at least like 25% of my friends here have used the phrase before so my sincere apologies and no offense, but the phrase "vibe shift" is particularly repulsive because it's used to "naturalize" one's personal desires for the future as a sort of neutral weather event.

Contrary Pancake had a great post: "You don't change minds with debate. You change minds by reaching around and striking people in the unconscious." and it's obviously what anyone using the phrase is trying to achieve, but in an ineffective and abortive way. Let's have dignity.

Being pedantic about facts and data is a lot more palatable to me than everyone trying to play magician and manipulate others into also pretending his beliefs are part of an ascendant organic cultural movement spontaneously emerging. You ought to *actually* change people's minds.

A lot of this probably just stems from overcorrecting the 2016 "facts don't care about your feelings" rhetoric and realizing most people are driven by feelings and mystique instead then trying to harvest those powers by speaking into power, the result being this polemical kitsch.
